---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import Disclaimer from '../../components/Disclaimer.astro'
import VerifyBadge from '../../components/VerifyBadge.astro'

// Annual TCD vehicle licence fees (statutory, separate from insurance).
// Motor Car Act 1951, Schedule 2; rates effective 1 April 2026. A representative
// subset of the nine car classes (graded by length, not engine size) plus cycles.
const licenceFees = [
  { v: 'Private car — Class A (smallest)', fee: '$246.35' },
  { v: 'Private car — Class E (mid-size)', fee: '$827.93' },
  { v: 'Private car — Class H (largest)', fee: '$1,359.29' },
  { v: 'Private car — Class I (electric / hybrid)', fee: '$1,518.26' },
  { v: 'Motorcycle — up to 100cc', fee: '$91.08' },
  { v: 'Auxiliary cycle — 50cc (privately owned)', fee: '$61.32' },
]
---

<Base
  title="Insurance in Bermuda: Car, Bike & Home"
  description="What car and scooter insurance costs in Bermuda, the mandatory third-party motor cover required by law, annual vehicle licensing fees, and home contents insurance — with sources and verification dates."
>
  <section class="hero hero--image" style="padding-block: var(--space-16); --hero-image: url('/Pilot.BM/images/scooters.webp');">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/move" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Moving</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Insurance</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Insurance in Bermuda</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Car, scooter, and home — what's legally required, what it roughly costs,
        and the fees people forget to budget for.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">

      <!-- REQUIRED disclaimer above the fold -->
      <Disclaimer variant="relocation" />

      <!-- Honest framing on premiums -->
      <div class="alert alert-warning" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <strong>On premiums:</strong> Bermuda's insurers do not publish motor rate tables — every
        premium depends on the driver, the vehicle, the claims history, and the excess you choose.
        The ranges on this page are <strong>realistic market estimates, not quoted prices</strong>.
        Treat them as a budgeting starting point and get a direct quote before you commit.
      </div>

      <!-- Mandatory cover -->
      <h2>Third-party motor cover is mandatory — by law</h2>
      <p>
        It is illegal to use a motor vehicle on a Bermuda road without third-party liability
        insurance. This is set out in the <strong>Motor Car Insurance (Third-Party Risks) Act 1943</strong>,
        and — importantly for new arrivals — it applies to <strong>50cc auxiliary cycles (scooters)</strong>
        just as it does to cars. The cheap scooter most expats buy or rent still has to be insured.
      </p>
      <p>
        The law sets a statutory minimum your policy must reach — it must cover at least
        <strong>$375,000 per person</strong> and <strong>$750,000 per accident</strong> for death,
        injury, or property damage caused by your vehicle. In practice insurers sell far higher
        third-party limits (commonly up to around $5&nbsp;million on comprehensive policies), so you'll
        rarely be at the bare legal floor.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        Legal mandate and minimum limits: Motor Car Insurance (Third-Party Risks) Act 1943, ss.&nbsp;3–4.
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-30" sourceLabel="bermudalaws.bm" sourceUrl="https://www.bermudalaws.bm" />
      </p>

      <!-- What it costs -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">What car and scooter insurance roughly costs</h2>
      <p>
        Two levels of cover are sold: <strong>third-party only</strong> (the legal minimum) and
        <strong>comprehensive</strong> (adds damage to your own vehicle, plus hurricane/flood, theft,
        windscreen, and uninsured-driver cover). Most car owners choose comprehensive; many scooter
        riders run third-party only on an older bike.
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrapper" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Vehicle &amp; cover</th>
              <th>Estimated annual premium</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Scooter / small motorcycle</strong> (50cc, third-party)</td>
              <td>~$150–450</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Private car — third-party only</strong></td>
              <td>~$400–900</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Private car — comprehensive</strong></td>
              <td>~$900–2,500+</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="unverified" style="font-size: var(--text-sm);">
        [These ranges are editorial market estimates — insurers do not publish motor rates. Your actual
        premium depends on the driver, the vehicle's value, your claims history, and the excess. Get a
        direct quote.]
      </p>
      <p>
        The biggest lever on price is the <strong>no-claims discount</strong>, which insurers do
        advertise: up to roughly <strong>60–65% off a car policy</strong> and up to <strong>20% off a
        cycle policy</strong> for a clean record built up year by year. Bundling home and motor, paying
        a higher excess, and buying online can each trim a little more.
      </p>

      <!-- Licensing fees -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Don't forget the annual licence fee</h2>
      <p>
        Separate from insurance, every vehicle pays an <strong>annual licence (registration) fee</strong>
        to the Transport Control Department (TCD). For cars this is graded by the vehicle's
        <strong>length</strong> (not engine size) across nine classes. These are hard statutory figures —
        the rates below took effect <strong>1 April 2026</strong> (a 10% cut on the prior year):
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrapper" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Vehicle</th>
              <th>Annual licence fee</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {licenceFees.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td>{row.v}</td>
                <td>{row.fee}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        Motor Car Act 1951, Schedule 2 (licence duties), effective 1 April 2026; auxiliary-cycle fee
        per the TCD renewal schedule. One-off examination fees also apply at first licensing
        ($38 for a cycle/motorcycle, $54 for a car).
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-30" sourceLabel="gov.bm (TCD)" sourceUrl="https://www.gov.bm/online-services/renew-your-vehicle-licence" />
      </p>

      <!-- One car rule cross-link -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">The one-car rule doesn't apply to scooters</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda restricts car ownership to <strong>one private car per household</strong> (tied to your
        property's Assessment Number). What surprises people in a good way: <strong>cycles and
        motorcycles are exempt</strong> from that limit. Each licensed rider in a household can have their
        own scooter, even if the household's single car slot is already taken. For many couples and
        shared households, a scooter each is the practical answer.
      </p>
      <div class="alert alert-info" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
        The one-car rule is the single biggest surprise for movers. We cover it in full —
        Assessment Numbers, how the slot works, and the import maths — in
        <a href="/Pilot.BM/move/tools/assessment-number">The Car Trap</a>.
      </div>

      <!-- Import duty -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Importing a vehicle: the duty stings</h2>
      <p>
        If you ship a car in, import duty dwarfs the insurance cost. Passenger cars are dutiable at
        roughly <strong>75% on the first $10,000 of assessed value and 150% on the value above that</strong>;
        motorcycles are lower (around 33.5%). Electric cars get their import duty halved as a concession.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        Import-duty rates derive from the Customs Tariff Act 1970 (Chapter 87).
        <span class="unverified">[One source cites the first-band threshold as $12,000 rather than $10,000 — verify the current figure with Bermuda Customs before relying on it.]</span>
        <VerifyBadge date="2026-06-30" sourceLabel="gov.bm Customs Tariff" sourceUrl="https://www.gov.bm/schedules-customs-tariff-act-1970" />
      </p>

      <!-- Licence / age -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Who can ride or drive</h2>
      <ul class="prose" style="padding-left: var(--space-6); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
        <li>You must be <strong>18</strong> to hold a licence to drive a car or ride a motorcycle (over 50cc).</li>
        <li>You must be <strong>16</strong> to ride a <strong>50cc auxiliary cycle</strong> — the typical first scooter.</li>
        <li>
          New residents register with TCD where they live. Visitors cannot rent or drive cars at all;
          rental scooter liveries typically set their own minimum age (often 18) and don't require a
          foreign licence — confirm with the specific operator.
          <span class="unverified">[rental-age policy varies by livery]</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        See the visitor view in <a href="/Pilot.BM/visit/getting-around">Getting Around Bermuda</a>.
      </p>

      <!-- Home insurance -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Home and contents insurance</h2>
      <p>
        If you're renting — which most expats do at first — your landlord insures the building, but
        <strong>your possessions are your own responsibility</strong>. Home-contents policies are
        widely available and worth having on an island where hurricane and flood exposure is a real,
        if infrequent, risk. Bermuda buildings are famously storm-built, but contents cover protects
        what's inside.
      </p>
      <p>
        The same insurers that write motor cover write home and contents, and most offer a discount
        (commonly around 10%) for bundling home with your car policy. Get a contents valuation roughly
        right before you quote, and ask specifically how wind and flood are treated.
        <span class="unverified">[bundle discounts and terms vary by insurer — confirm directly]</span>
      </p>

      <!-- Who the insurers are -->
      <h2 style="margin-top: var(--space-10);">Who to get a quote from</h2>
      <p>
        The main personal-lines insurers and brokers in Bermuda are <strong>Argus</strong>,
        <strong>BF&amp;M</strong>, <strong>Colonial / CG Insurance</strong>, and
        <strong>Freisenbruch</strong>. Brokers are commonly used and can shop several markets for you.
      </p>
      <div class="alert alert-info" style="margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">
        <strong>Heads up on branding:</strong> Argus and BF&amp;M have been consolidating under the
        <strong>Allshores</strong> group, so you may encounter either the legacy names or the new one
        while the transition settles.
        <span class="unverified">[corporate rebrand in progress — verify the current entity when you apply]</span>
      </div>

      <!-- Directory CTA -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-surface); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-top: var(--space-10);">
        <h2 style="margin-bottom: var(--space-3); font-size: var(--text-2xl);">Insurers in the directory</h2>
        <p style="margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">
          Contact details for Bermuda's insurers and brokers — motor, home, and health — are in the
          Pilot.BM directory.
        </p>
        <a href="/Pilot.BM/directory?filter=insurance" class="btn btn-primary">Browse insurers in the directory →</a>
      </div>

      <!-- Related -->
      <div style="margin-top: var(--space-10); padding-top: var(--space-6); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);"><strong>Related</strong></p>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/move/cost-of-living">Cost of Living</a> ·
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/move/tools/assessment-number">The Car Trap</a> ·
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/move/healthcare">Healthcare &amp; the mandatory health benefit</a> ·
          <a href="/Pilot.BM/move/banking">Banking</a>
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
